#block(breakable: false)[

== The Constraint Engine Principle

Technology is your story's constraint engine. Every technological decision either adds or removes an obstacle between your characters, and obstacles are what romance feeds off of. But here's the thing that makes technology constraints so powerful: they almost never function solely as obstacles. They also serve as intimacy accelerators. The same dragon bond that forces Violet and Xaden into proximity in #emph[Fourth Wing] is also the reason they spend enough time together to move from suspicion to reluctant trust to something more. The constraint slows down the romance but at the same time fuels it.

Consider it this way. A world where characters can teleport, communicate instantly, heal any wound, and lock doors so no one can get in is a world without distance, longing, danger, and stolen moments. That's a world with very few romantic constraints. Now picture the opposite: a world where it takes weeks to travel, letters can be read by others before they arrive, a fever could kill you and the walls are thin enough to hear someone whispering. That's a world creating tension, vulnerability, and yearning on every page.

This doesn't mean low-tech is automatically better than high-tech. What it means is that every technology choice has a romantic consequence, and you should be making those choices deliberately. If you provide your characters with instant communication, you've removed the ache of waiting, so you'll need to find another source of tension. If you make healing magic simple, then you can't use injury as your constraint, so something else will have to be. The constraint engine only stalls when everything is easy. Find something that is difficult.

Technology constraints work through two mechanisms: #strong[containment] and #strong[conversion]. Containment is how your world manufactures unavoidable contact. Inn rooms, sleeping bags, escorted travel, shared dragon flights, carriages where there's no space to move away from each other. Conversion is how physical proximity gets translated into an emotional beat. Injury requiring touch, touch legitimising confession, shared meals revealing class difference, bathing creating vulnerability.

Effective romantasy technology choices do both simultaneously. The snowbound inn in #emph[A Court of Mist and Fury] contains Feyre and Rhysand in the same bed while converting that closeness into confessional pacing. And the sleeping bag in #emph[From Blood and Ash] contains Poppy and Hawke while converting body heat into erotic tension. Once you get the containment right, the conversion follows.

Your most powerful romantic technology choices will also create asymmetry: one character has some advantage over the other in terms of access to information or resources. She can send messages through enchanted mirrors; he has to wait for a letter that takes three weeks. He lives in a palace with locked doors; she sleeps in a crowded room with four other people. Think of Feyre arriving in Prythian in #emph[A Court of Thorns and Roses], suddenly immersed in a world of Fae magic, wealth, and technology she's never encountered, unable to read the simplest sign. This disparity between what Tamlin views as normal and what overwhelms Feyre drives their early dynamic. His world is alien, and her disorientation creates both vulnerability and resentment. The disparity between worlds creates friction, dependency, and curiosity; all the raw material romance is built from.

As you work through this section, keep the Constraint Engine principle in mind. Before you can map your world's romantic constraints, though, you need to know what technology actually exists. The questions that follow will help you establish that foundation, starting with the big picture and working toward the specific, personal, and emotional.

