Keep these channels and patterns in mind as you work through the sections ahead. You'll return to apply them directly to your world once you've established what technology actually exists.


== A Note Before You Begin


Not every question in this section will apply to your world. A futuristic setting won't need to answer questions about candlelight; a pre-industrial world won't deal with mass communication. Skip what doesn't serve your story! But pay attention to the questions that make you uncomfortable or uncertain. Those are often the ones that reveal the most interesting constraints.


=== Quick Guide to What You Need


#strong[Every story needs:] How people travel, how they communicate, and what daily life looks like.


#strong[If distance separates your characters:] Focus on Movement & Distance and Communication & Connection.


#strong[If surveillance or privacy matters:] Focus on Privacy & Observation.


#strong[If your characters come from different social classes:] Focus on how technology access differs in Daily Life.


#strong[If you're not sure yet:] Start with the Brain Dump and Overall Technology Level. You can always come back.


== Common Mistakes with Technology


#mistake-box(
  title: "Mistake #1: The Convenience Trap",
  fix: [Every convenient technology needs a cost, a limit, or a gap. Teleportation works but is agonisingly painful. Healing magic can mend bones but can't cure illness. The communication spell requires rare ingredients that are running out. #emph[Fourth Wing] does this well: wyverns give riders extraordinary power, but the bonding process kills most candidates, signets come with physical costs, and Violet's body is genuinely fragile in ways that magic can't fully fix. The convenience exists, but it's never free. Give your reader a reason to worry.],
)[
  Magic or technology solves every problem. Instant teleportation, perfect healing, unbreakable privacy wards, flawless communication. Nothing is hard. If nothing is hard, nothing is at stake. Distance means nothing if you can teleport. Injury means nothing if healing is instant. Separation means nothing if you can talk any time. The constraint engine stalls and the romance has to generate all its tension from pure interpersonal conflict, which gets exhausting fast.
]


#mistake-box(
  title: "Mistake #2: The Museum Piece",
  fix: [For every technology you describe, ask yourself: "How does this affect my characters' ability to be together, communicate, or stay safe?" If the answer is "it doesn't," cut it or rethink it.],
)[
  Technology is described in detail (the canal system, the printing press, the enchanted forges) but never actually affects the characters or the romance. It's worldbuilding decoration. Readers don't care about your canal system unless it determines whether two characters can reach each other. Technology that doesn't create or remove obstacles is just furniture.
]


#mistake-box(
  title: "Mistake #3: The Inconsistency Problem",
  fix: [Establish your rules early. Write them down for yourself. Constraint-driven tension is strongest when the constraint has an in-world logic (dragon biology, ward physics, reputation systems, institutional rules) and when it forces decisions that reveal character under pressure. When you need the plot to go differently, change the circumstances, not the rules. The message doesn't arrive faster; the character finds a faster method and pays for it. The healing doesn't fail; the injury is of a type that healing can't fix.],
)[
  Technology rules shift to serve the plot. Messages arrive in hours when the plot needs urgency, but take weeks when the plot needs separation. Healing magic works perfectly in chapter three but mysteriously fails in chapter twelve. Readers track these rules even when they don't realise it. Inconsistency breaks trust and makes the romantic obstacles feel manufactured rather than organic. #strong[What does your world's convenience cost?] #emph[The Convenience Trap stalls your romance when everything is easy. For every powerful or convenient technology in your world, identify what limits it, what it costs, or where it fails. If you can't find a cost, your constraint engine may be stalling.] | Convenient Technology | What It Makes Easy | The Cost, Limit, or Gap | How the Cost Affects Your Romance | |---|---|---|---| | #emph[Wyvern bond gives riders extraordinary power (Fourth Wing)] | #emph[Travel, communication, combat] | #emph[Bonding kills most candidates; signets have physical costs; Violet's body is genuinely fragile] | #emph[Power comes with real danger. Every flight could kill her, which keeps the stakes alive] | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | #strong[Technology Self-Check] #emph[Run through each technology you've described in this section. If you can't answer the first question, rethink whether you need it. If you struggle with the second, write down your rules now before inconsistency creeps in.] | Technology | Does it affect your characters' ability to be together, communicate, or stay safe? (If no, cut or rethink) | What are its rules? (Write them down so they stay consistent) | |---|---|---| | | | | | | | | | | | |
]


