== Bodies & Vulnerability


Technology and the body intersect in medicine and reproduction; the body is also where romance lives. How will the injuries and health challenges facing your characters affect them? How will those issues be treated? What will be the emotional ramifications of physical intimacy? These determine some of the most emotionally charged moments in your story. A world where all wounds can be healed removes all of the risk from injury and makes your characters invincible. A world where a fever could result in death is a world of vulnerability and will break open your characters.


Caretaking is such a powerful element of romantasy, for it turns romantic feelings into actions. When a character shows up to stay with another injured character, or hold them, or tend to their injuries, or teach them how to ground themselves, this proves their love in ways that talking can't. In #emph[Fourth Wing], Violet finds herself in a hospital bed after being wounded during a battle, and Xaden is there beside her. This is a classic hurt/comfort beat where the act of caring is evidence of attachment. In #emph[From Blood and Ash], Hawke physically calms Poppy down after she becomes overwhelmed by the emotional response of a crowd, and this act of caring reads as co-regulation in a society where she's unable to openly express herself due to the dangers posed by her abilities. Hawke later gives Poppy part of his own blood to save her life after she's been stabbed, and in doing so he not only heals her but also reveals much about himself and transforms the entire nature of the relationship.


Sophie cares for Benedict in #emph[Bridgerton] while he's suffering from a fever at an isolated cottage, which is the Regency era equivalent of "the only healer within a reasonable distance." Fever is inherently a sensory experience: heat, wet hair, and delirious speech. And fever has a unique ability to cause people to confess things they'd never normally admit to, even though they may say things in a state of delirium that they'd never say while sober. The limited medical capabilities of the time (rest, warmth, broth, constant observation) create an intimate environment because the only places where this can occur are away from the prying eyes of chaperones and social expectations of propriety. Isolated locations like cottages and inns represent a form of low-technology containment.


When writing these types of scenes, keep in mind that medical environments tend to become confession environments. When people are sick or injured, they rely on others for care and support, and this dependence often creates a need for compromise or a need to reveal information that changes everything.


